  "notes": "Swahili (Kiswahili). Bantu lingua franca of East Africa; official language of Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda, DRC, Rwanda. ~200 million total speakers. KEY FEATURES: (1) FIVE-VOWEL SYSTEM: a/e/i/o/u; e=[ɛ], o=[ɔ] (fully open). (2) PRENASALIZED STOPS: mb/nd/nj/ng are single phonemes, may appear word-initially. (3) SYLLABIC NASALS: m- and n- prefixes are syllabic in noun classes (e.g., mtu /m̩.tu/). (4) NG vs NG': <ng'> = [ŋ] (velar nasal alone), <ng> = [ŋɡ] (prenasalized stop). (5) ARABIC LOANS: dh=[ð], th=[θ], gh=[ɣ] from Arabic via coastal contact (Swahili Coast trade). (6) NO TONES: Standard Swahili (Kiunguja/Zanzibar-based) is not tonal, unlike many other Bantu languages. (7) NOUN CLASS SYSTEM: prefixes (m-/wa-, ki-/vi-, n-, etc.) mark noun class but do not affect grapheme-phoneme mapping.",
